Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1. Custom "Cancel" back button + confirmation dialog:**

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="YourApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding NavigateBackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

**2. ViewModel (or code-behind) logic:**

```csharp
// EditProductViewModel.cs
public ICommand NavigateBackCommand { get; }
public bool HasUnsavedChanges { get; set; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    NavigateBackCommand = new Command(async () => await TryNavigateBack());
}

private async Task TryNavigateBack()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and leave?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return; // cancel navigation
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoBackAsync();
}
```

**3. Intercept the Android/hardware back button too:**

```csharp
// EditProductPage.xaml.cs
protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
{
    // Fire the same command so both paths share logic
    if (BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm)
    {
        vm.NavigateBackCommand.Execute(null);
        return true; // true = we handled it, cancel default navigation
    }
    return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Shell.BackButtonBehavior` replaces the arrow with a "Cancel" text button and routes taps through your command.
- `OnBackButtonPressed` catches the Android hardware/gesture back button (it doesn't fire on iOS — iOS uses the shell back button, which is already handled by `BackButtonBehavior`).
- Returning `true` from `OnBackButtonPressed` cancels the default navigation.
